{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563626"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16841"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16841"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.13,0.12,0.31,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67249"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52701"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3902"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9330"},{"type":"tags","id":"9331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67249"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with a three-month history of progressive abdominal distension and discomfort. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a firm, mobile mass arising from the pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound shows a 6cm complex ovarian cyst. Cancer antigen 125 is 20 kU/L (0-35). She undergoes laparoscopic ovarian cystectomy. During the procedure, there is inadvertent spillage of cyst contents into the peritoneal cavity. The cyst is completely removed. Peritoneal washings are taken. The abdomen otherwise appears normal. Histopathology reveals a moderately differentiated serous adenocarcinoma. All peritoneal washings are negative for malignant cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the staging and implications for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stage IA - no further treatment required","Stage IA - requires chemotherapy","Stage IIIC - requires chemotherapy","Stage IC - requires chemotherapy","Stage IC - no further treatment required"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates the importance of intraoperative cyst rupture in ovarian cancer staging. The International Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics (FIGO) staging system is used for ovarian cancer, where stage I disease is confined to the ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IC - requires chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. When an ovarian cancer cyst ruptures during surgery, even if the disease appears otherwise confined to the ovary, it is automatically upstaged to IC. This upstaging occurs because tumour cells may have spread into the peritoneal cavity during rupture. Stage IC requires adjuvant chemotherapy due to the risk of microscopic peritoneal dissemination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IA - no further treatment required\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate if the cyst was removed intact without rupture and the tumour was confined to one ovary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IA - requires chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as stage IA disease (confined to one ovary, no rupture) typically does not require adjuvant chemotherapy if completely resected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IC - no further treatment required\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because stage IC always requires adjuvant chemotherapy due to the risk of microscopic spread.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IIIC - requires chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate if there was evidence of peritoneal metastases or lymph node involvement, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case also highlights the importance of preoperative risk assessment of ovarian masses. When cancer is suspected, referral to a gynecologic oncologist for primary surgery is preferred to optimise surgical staging and reduce the risk of cyst rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intraoperative cyst rupture in ovarian cancer automatically upstages the disease to stage IC regardless of other findings.","Stage IC ovarian cancer requires adjuvant chemotherapy even if the tumour was otherwise confined to the ovary.","Preoperative assessment of ovarian masses should include cancer risk stratification to determine appropriate surgical approach and operator."],"references":["Berek JS, Renz M, Kehoe S, Kumar L, Friedlander M. Cancer of the ovary, fallopian tube, and peritoneum: 2021 update. Int J Gynaecol Obstet. 2021 Oct;155 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):61-85. doi: 10.1002/ijgo.13878. PMID: 34669199; PMCID: PMC9298325."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52701"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16841"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52701"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T10:45:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T10:47:10+10:30"},"relationships":